               <head>Two works on alchemy, Judeo-Arabic</head>



               <msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85003265" rend="visible">



                  <summary>Two works on alchemy, in Arabic in Hebrew characters. </summary>



                  <textLang mainLang="jrb-Hebr"/>



                  <msItem rend="">
                     <locus from="1r" to="27v"/>
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="en">Abū ‘Abdullāh ibn Umayl al-Tamīmī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="he">אבן אמיל, אבו עבדאללה</persName>
                     </author>

                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">al-Mā’ al-waraqī wa-al-arḍ al-najmīyah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="he">אלמא אלורקי ואלארץ אלנג'מיה</title>

                     <note>
                        <p>The work consists of the following sections: an introductory portion
                           (describing the winged creatures of the ceiling and walls of the Temple
                           at Busir), folio 2r; the pictured winged creatures, with brief
                           explanations, folio 3v-4v; a commentary by the author of the original
                           work, folio 4v; a set of comments on the same subject, folio 21v. There
                           are three additional portions starting with folio 27r. </p>
                     </note>

                     <decoNote type="illustration">
                        <locus n="3v, 4r"/>An illustration of winged creatures, in red and black
                        ink. </decoNote>
                  </msItem>



                  <msItem rend="">



                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="en">Al-Yamani, Ismail</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="he">אסמאעיל אלימני</persName>
                     </author>



                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Al-tadbir</title>



                     <title xml:lang="he">אלתדביר </title>



                     <locus from="28r" to="43v"/>



                     <note>
                        <p>The heading is followed by a table of chapters, with titles in red. The
                           first chapter begins on folio 30v, the second on folio 35r, the third on
                           folio 37r, chapters four to six are omitted, and the seventh on folio
                           40v. </p>
                     </note>



                  </msItem>



               </msContents>



